# Strict TypeScript + ESLint

- Always write TypeScript in strict mode style; avoid `any` unless absolutely unavoidable.
- Prefer explicit types for props, function params, returns, and shared data structures.
- Handle `undefined` and `null` safely with proper guards.
- Do not bypass type safety with unsafe casts unless there is a clear, documented reason.

# ESLint Policy

- Never add `eslint-disable`, `eslint-disable-next-line`, or `@ts-ignore` as a shortcut.
- Fix the real issue instead of suppressing warnings/errors.
- Keep files free of unused imports, variables, and dead code.

# Example

```tsx
// Good: typed props and no suppression comments
type UserCardProps = {
  name: string
  age?: number
}

function UserCard({ name, age }: UserCardProps) {
  return <p>{age ? `${name} (${age})` : name}</p>
}
```
